{
  "id": "american-standard-silver-thermostat",
  "brand": "American Standard",
  "model": "Silver SI",
  "equipment_type": "air-handler",
  "symptom": "Thermostat screen is completely blank \u2014 no display, no response to any button. HVAC system is fully dead (no heat, no cool, no fan). Breaker is on. Other circuits in the house work fine.",
  "diagnosis": "Blown 3A or 5A fuse on the furnace/air-handler control board. The thermostat gets its 24V power from the R (red) wire \u2014 if the board's transformer fuse blows, the thermostat loses power. Common cause: a shorted thermostat wire (pinched during renovation, critter damage) or a miswired thermostat swap.",
  "part_number": "3A automotive blade fuse (ATC/ATO type) \u2014 keep spares on the truck. If fuse blows repeatedly, trace the short.",
  "procedure": [
    "At the air handler / furnace, kill power at the switch.",
    "Open the control board compartment. Locate the low-voltage fuse \u2014 typically a small automotive blade fuse (3A or 5A, purple or tan) near the transformer.",
    "Pull the fuse and test with a multimeter for continuity. If open = blown fuse.",
    "Before replacing: disconnect the R (red) wire from the board terminal strip. Measure resistance from R to C at the thermostat end \u2014 should be open (infinite). If it reads near 0 ohms, there's a short in the thermostat cable.",
    "Inspect thermostat wiring at both ends for pinched, nicked, or touching conductors. Fix any short found.",
    "If the wiring checks out, install a new 3A fuse (match the original rating \u2014 do NOT upsize).",
    "Restore power. Verify 24\u201328V AC between R and C at the thermostat.",
    "The thermostat should power on within 5 seconds. If it does, run a test cycle (heat or cool).",
    "If the fuse blows again immediately, the short is still present \u2014 check the outdoor unit wiring, contactor coil, and zone damper motors."
  ],
  "safety_notes": [
    "Control boards can have 120V or 240V line voltage on the same board as the 24V section \u2014 power must be off before touching.",
    "Never replace a 3A fuse with a higher-rated fuse \u2014 the fuse protects the transformer, which is expensive to replace.",
    "If there's evidence of arcing or burn marks on the board, the board itself may need replacement."
  ],
  "estimated_minutes": 20,
  "tags": [
    "thermostat",
    "blank screen",
    "no power",
    "blown fuse",
    "24V",
    "american standard",
    "Silver SI",
    "control board",
    "dead system"
  ],
